        <p>
          For readers including <xref ref="ch-the-next-generation-method"/> on computing <m>\mathcal{R}_0</m>, you may wish to try the steps for computing <m>\mathcal{R}_0</m> in the SEIR model. The answer appears below, yet this is a great time to test yourself. Completing the steps and confirming your results below lets you gain practice now, before perhaps trying to compute <m>\mathcal{R}_0</m> on a future model where no answer is given. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The resulting <m>\mathcal{R}_0</m> formula is:
        </p>
        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="eq-R0-seir">\mathcal{R}_0 \amp = \frac{\beta N}{\gamma} \mbox{ for our SEIR model}. </mrow>
        </mdn>
        <p>
          The formula in <xref ref="eq-R0-seir"/> can be rearranged in order to use information about <m>\mathcal{R}_0</m>, <m>\gamma</m>, and <m>N</m> to compute a reasonable range of <m>\beta</m> values in a model. We have seen how to estimate <m>\gamma</m> and <m>\kappa</m> in <xref ref="eq-gamma-estimate"/>, <xref ref="eq-gamma-estimate-2"/>, <xref ref="eq-kappa-estimate"/>, and <xref ref="eq-kappa-estimate"/>. We therefore have the ability to determine the parameter values for an SEIR model of a specific outbreak. Try this in <xref ref="activity-seir-model-pertussis-setup"/>.
        </p>

        <activity xml:id="activity-seir-model-pertussis-setup">
